<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(2) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
State education services.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Of the funds allocated for any program year for sections 202(c)(1)(C) and 262(c)(1)(C) of the Act to carry out activities
pursuant to section 123(d)(2)(B) of the Act_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Not less than 50 percent shall be expended for the cost of direct training services; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Not more than 20 percent shall be expended for the cost of administration. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The limitations specified in paragraph (a)(2) of this section shall apply to the combined total of funds allocated
for sections 202(c)(1)(C) and 262(c)(1)(C) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
SDA allocations.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1) In applying the title II&hyph;A and II&hyph;C cost limitations specified in section 108(b)(4) of the Act, the
funds allocated to a service delivery area shall be net of any: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Transfers made in accordance with sections 206, 256, and 266 of the Act; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Reallocations made by the Governor in accordance with section 109(a) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The limitations specified in paragraph (b)(1) of this section shall apply separately to the funds allocated for
title II&hyph;A and title II&hyph;C programs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The title II&hyph;B administrative cost limitation of 15 percent shall be 15 percent of the funds allocated for
any program year to a service delivery area, excluding any funds transferred to title II&hyph;C in accordance with
section 256 of the Act (section 253(a)(3)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c)(1) The State shall establish a system to regularly assess compliance with the cost limitations including periodic
review and corrective action, as necessary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) States and service delivery areas shall have the 3-year period of fund availability to comply with the cost limitations
in section 108 of the Act and paragraphs (a) and (b) of this section (section 161(b)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) Administrative costs incurred by a community-based organization or non-profit service provider shall not be
included in the limitation described in section 108(b)(4)(A) of the Act if: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Such costs are incurred under an agreement that meets the requirements of section 141(d)(3)(C) (i) and (ii) of
the Act; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The total administrative expenditures of the service delivery area, including the administrative expenditures
of such community-based organizations or non-profit service providers, do not exceed 25 percent of the funds allocated
to the service delivery area for the program year of allocation; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The total direct training expenditures of the service delivery area, including the direct training expenditures
of such community-based organizations or non-profit service providers, is equal to or exceeds 50 percent of the funds
allocated to the service delivery area for the program year less one-half of the percentage by which the total administrative
expenditures of the service delivery area exceeds 20 percent. For example, if the total administrative expenditures
of the service delivery area is 24 percent, then the total direct training expenditures of the service delivery area
must be at least 48 percent. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) The provisions of this section do not apply to any title III programs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(f) The provisions of this section do not apply to any designated SDA which served as a concentrated employment program
grantee for a rural area under the Comprehensive Employment and Training Act (section 108(d)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.450 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Program income. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Definition of program income.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1) Program income means income received by the recipient or subrecipient that is directly generated by a grant or
subgrant supported activity, or earned only as a result of the grant or subgrant. Program income includes: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Income from fees for services performed and from conferences; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Income from the use or rental of real or personal property acquired with grant or subgrant funds; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) Income from the sale of commodities or items fabricated under a grant or subgrant; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00122 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(iv) Revenues earned by a governmental or non-profit service provider under either a fixed-price or reimbursable
award that are in excess of the actual costs incurred in providing the services; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(v) Interest income earned on advances of JTPA funds. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Program income does not include: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Rebates, credits, discounts, refunds, etc., or interest earned on any of them, which shall be credited in accordance
with &sect;627.435(d), Cost principles and allowable costs; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Taxes, special assessments, levies, fines, and other such governmental revenues raised by a recipient or subrecipient;
or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) Income from royalties and license fees for copyrighted material, patents, patent applications, trademarks,
and inventions developed by a recipient or subrecipient. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Property.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Proceeds from the sale of property shall be handled in accordance with the requirements of &sect;627.465 of this part,
Property management standards. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Cost of generating program income.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Costs incidental to the generation of program income may be deducted, if not already charged to the grant, from gross
income to determine program income. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Use of program income.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1)(i) A recipient or subrecipient may retain any program income earned by the recipient or subrecipient only if such
income is added to the funds committed to the particular JTPA grant or subgrant and title under which it was earned and
such income is used for that title's purposes and under the terms and conditions applicable to the use of the grant funds.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) A State may use interest it earns on JTPA funds, deposited by the United States to the State's account, to satisfy
the requirement at 31 U.S.C. 6503(c) that the State pay interest on such deposits. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) The classification of costs in &sect;&sect;627.440 and 631.13 shall apply to the use of program income. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iv) The administrative cost limitation in &sect;&sect;627.445 and 631.14 shall apply to the use of program income,
except that program income used in accordance with paragraph (c)(1)(ii) of this section shall be exempt from the administrative
cost limitations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) Program income generated under title II may also be used to satisfy the matching requirement of section 123(b)
of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Program income shall be used prior to the submission of the final report for the funding period of the program year
of funds to which the earnings are attributable. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) If the subrecipient that earned program income cannot use such income for JTPA purposes, the recipient may permit
another entity to use the program income for JTPA purposes. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) Program income not used in accordance with the requirements of this section shall be remitted to the Department
of Labor. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Program and other income after the funding period.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Rental income and user fees on real and personal property acquired with JTPA funds shall continue to be JTPA program
income in subsequent funding periods. There are no Federal requirements governing the disposition of all other income
that is earned after the end of the funding period. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.455 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Reports required. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
General.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The Governor shall report to DOL pursuant to instructions issued by DOL. Reports shall be submitted no more frequently
than quarterly, in accordance with section 165(f) of the Act, and within 45 calendar days after the end of the report
period. Additional reporting requirements for title III are set forth at &sect;631.15 of this chapter. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) A recipient may impose different forms or formats, shorter due dates, and more frequent reporting requirements
on subrecipients, however, the recipient is required to meet the reporting requirements imposed on it by DOL. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) DOL may provide computer outputs to recipients to expedite or contribute to the accuracy of reporting. DOL may
accept the required information from recipients in electronically reported format or computer printouts instead
of prescribed forms. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Financial reports.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1) Financial reports for programs under titles I, II, and III shall be submitted to DOL by each State quarterly and
by program year of appropriation. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Each recipient shall report program outlays on an accrual basis. If the recipient's accounting records are not
normally kept on the accrual basis, the recipient shall develop such accrual information through an analysis of the
documentation on hand. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) A final financial report is required 90 days after the expiration of a funding period (see &sect;627.485 of this
part, Closeout). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Pursuant to section 104(b)(13) of the Act, the SDA shall annually report to the Governor. Among other items, this
report shall include information on the extent to which the SDA has met the goals for the training and training-related
placement of women in nontraditional employment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.460 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Requirements for records. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (a) Records, including the records identified in section 165(g) of the Act, shall be retained in accordance with section
165(e) of the Act. In establishing the time period of record retention requirements for records of subrecipients,
the State may either: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Impose the time limitation requirement of section 165(e) of the Act; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Require that subrecipient records for each funding period be retained for 3 years after the subrecipient submits
to the awarding agency its final expenditure report for that funding period. Records for nonexpendable property
shall be retained for a period of three years after final disposition of the property. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The Governor shall ensure that the records under this section shall be retained beyond the prescribed period if
any litigation or audit is begun or if a claim is instituted involving the grant or agreement covered by the records.
In these instances, the Governor shall ensure that the records shall be retained until the litigation, audit, or claim
has been finally resolved. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) In the event of the termination of the relationship with a subrecipient, the Governor or SDA or title III SSG shall
be responsible for the maintenance and retention of the records of any subrecipient unable to retain them. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Record storage.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Records shall be retained and stored in a manner which will preserve their integrity and admissibility as evidence
in any audit or other proceeding. The burden of production and authentication of the records shall be on the custodian
of the records. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00123 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(e) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Federal and awarding agencies' access to records
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
_(1) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Records of recipients and subrecipients
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. The awarding agency, the Department of Labor (including the Department of Labor's Office of Inspector General),
and the Comptroller General of the United States, or any of their authorized representatives, have the right of timely
and reasonable access to any books, documents, papers, computer records, or other records of recipients and subrecipients
that are pertinent to the grant, in order to conduct audits and examinations, and to make excerpts, transcripts, and
photocopies of such documents. This right also includes timely and reasonable access to recipient and subrecipient
personnel for the purpose of interview and discussion related to such documents. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Expiration of right of access. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The right of access in this section is not limited to the required retention period but shall last as long as the records
are retained. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.463 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Public access to records. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Public access. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Except as provided in paragraph (b) of this section, records maintained by recipients or subrecipients pursuant
to &sect;627.460 shall be made available to the public upon request, notwithstanding the provisions of State or local
law. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Exceptions. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This requirement does not apply to:
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Information, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy; or

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Trade secrets, or commercial or financial information, obtained from a person and privileged or confidential.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Fees. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
For processing of a request for a record under this section, a fee may be charged to the extent sufficient to recover
the cost applicable to processing such request (section 165(a)(4)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.465 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Property management standards. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
States and governmental subrecipients. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Real property, equipment, supplies, and intangible property acquired or produced after July 1, 1993, by States and
governmental subrecipients with JTPA funds shall be governed by the definitions and property requirements in the
DOL regulations at 29 CFR part 97, except that prior approval by the Department of Labor to acquire property is waived.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Nongovernmental subrecipients. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Except as provided in paragraph (c) of this section, real and personal property, including intangible property,
acquired or produced after July 1, 1993, by nongovernmental subrecipients with JTPA funds shall be governed by the
definitions and property management standards of OMB Circular A&hyph;110, as codified by administrative regulations
of the Department of Labor in 29 CFR Part 95, except that prior approval by the Department of Labor to acquire property
is waived. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Special provisions for property acquired under subgrants to commercial organizations._
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Scope. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This paragraph (c) applies to real and personal property other than supplies that are acquired or produced after July
1, 1993, under a JTPA subgrant to a commercial organization. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Property acquired by commercial subrecipients. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Title to property acquired or produced by a subrecipient that is a commercial organization shall vest in the awarding
agency, provided such agency is a governmental entity or nongovernmental organization that is not a commercial organization.
Property so acquired or produced shall be considered to be acquired or produced by the awarding agency and paragraph
(a) or (b) of this section, as appropriate, shall apply to that property. If the awarding agency is also a commercial
organization, title shall vest in the higher level, non-commercial awarding agency that made the subaward to the
commercial subrecipient. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (3) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Approval for acquisition. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
A subrecipient that is a commercial organization shall not acquire property subject to this section without the prior
approval of the awarding agency. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (d) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Notification to the Secretary of real property acquisitions. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Recipients shall notify the Secretary immediately upon acquisition of real property with JTPA funds, including
acquisitions by subrecipients. Such notification shall include the location of the real property and the Federal
share percentage. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Property procured before July 1, 1993. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) Personal or real property procured with JTPA funds or transferred from programs under the Comprehensive Employment
and Training Act must be used for purposes authorized by the Act. Subject to the Secretary's rights to such property,
the Governor shall maintain accountability for property in accordance with State procedures and the records retention
requirements of &sect;627.460 of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The JTPA program must be reimbursed the fair market value of any unneeded property retained by the Governor for
use in a non-JTPA program. The proceeds from the sale of any property or transfer of property to a non-JTPA program must
be used for purposes authorized under the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.470 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Performance standards. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
General. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Secretary shall prescribe performance standards for adult programs under title II&hyph;A, for youth programs
under title II&hyph;C, for dislocated worker programs under title III, and for older worker programs under section
204(d) of the Act. Any performance standards developed for employment competencies shall be based on such factors
as entry level skills and other hiring requirements. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00124 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(b) Pursuant to instructions and time lines issued by the Secretary, the Governor shall: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Collect the data necessary to set performance standards pursuant to section 106 of the Act; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Maintain records and submit reports required by sections 106(j)(3), 165(a)(3), (c)(1), and (d) and 121(b)(6)
of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Title II performance standards. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) The Governor shall establish SDA performance standards for title II within the parameters set by the Secretary
pursuant to sections 106(b) and (d) of the Act and apply the standards in accordance with section 202(c)(1)(B) of the
Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The Governor shall establish incentive award policies pursuant to section 106(b)(7) of the Act, except for programs
operated under section 204(d) of the Act. Pursuant to section 106(b)(8) of the Act, Governors may not consider standards
relating gross program expenditures to performance measures in making such incentive awards. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The Governor shall provide technical assistance to SDA's failing to meet performance standards established
by the Secretary for a given program year (section 106(j)(2)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4)(i) If an SDA fails to meet a prescribed number of the Secretary's performance standards for 2 consecutive years,
the Governor shall notify the Secretary and the service delivery area of the continued failure and impose a reorganization
plan (section 106(j)(4)).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) The number of standards deemed to constitute failure shall be specified by the Secretary biennially and shall
be based on an appropriate proportion of the total number established by the Secretary for that performance cycle.
In determining failure, the specified proportion shall be applied separately to each year of the two year cycle. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) A reorganization plan shall not be imposed for a failure to meet performance standards other than those established
by the Secretary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iv) A reorganization plan shall be considered to be imposed when, at a minimum: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(A) The problem or deficiency is identified, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(B) The problem is communicated to the SDA, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(C) The SDA is provided an initial statement of the actions or steps required and the timeframe within which they are
to be initiated. A final statement of required steps and actions is to be issued within 30 days. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d)(1) If the Governor does not impose a reorganization plan, required by paragraph (c)(4) of this section, within
90 days of notifying the Grant Officer of an SDA's continued failure to meet performance standards, the Grant Officer
shall develop and impose such a plan (section 106(j)(5)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Before imposing a reorganization plan, the Grant Officer shall notify the Governor and SDA in writing of the intent
to impose the plan and provide both parties the opportunity to submit comments within 30 days of receipt of the Grant
Officer's notice. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) An SDA subject to a reorganization plan under paragraphs (c)(4) or (d) of this section may, within 30 days of receiving
notice of such action, appeal to the Secretary to revise or rescind the reorganization plan under the procedures set
forth at &sect;627.471 of this subpart, Reorganization plan appeals (section 106(j)(6)(A)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(f) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Secretarial action to recapture or withhold funds. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) The Grant Officer shall recapture or withhold an amount not to exceed one-fifth of the State administration set-aside
allocated under sections 202(c)(1)(A) and 262(c)(1)(A) of the Act when: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) The Governor has failed to impose a reorganization plan under paragraph (c)(4) of this section, for the purposes
of providing technical assistance under a reorganization plan imposed by the Secretary (section 106(j)(5)(B));
or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) The Secretary determines in an appeal provided for at paragraph (e) of this section, and set forth at &sect;627.471
of this subpart, that the Governor has not provided appropriate technical assistance as required at section 106(j)(2)
(section 106(j)(6)(B)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2)(i) A Governor of a State that is subject to recapture or withholding under paragraph (f)(1) of this section may,
within 30 days of receipt of such notice, appeal such recapture or withholding to the Secretary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) The Secretary may consider any comments submitted by the Governor and shall make a decision within 45 days after
the appeal is received. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(g) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Title III performance standards. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) The Governor shall establish SSG performance standards for programs under title III within the parameters set
annually by the Secretary pursuant to section 106(c) and (d) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Any performance standard for programs under title III shall make appropriate allowances for the difference in
cost resulting from serving workers receiving needs-related payments authorized under &sect;631.20 of this chapter
(section 106(c)(2)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The Secretary annually shall certify compliance, if the program is in compliance, with the title III performance
standards established pursuant to paragraph (a) of section 322(a)(4) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) The Governor shall not establish standards for the operation of programs under title III that are inconsistent
with the performance standards established by the Secretary under provisions of section 106(c) of the Act (section
311(b)(8)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) When an SSG fails to meet performance standards for 2 consecutive years, the Governor may institute procedures
pursuant to the Governor's by-pass authority in accordance with &sect;631.38(b) of this chapter or require redesignation
of the substate grantee in accordance with &sect;631.35 of this chapter, as appropriate. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.471 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Reorganization plan appeals. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) A reorganization plan imposed by the Governor, as provided for at &sect;&sect;627.470(c)(4) or 627.477(b)(2)
of this part, or by the Secretary, as provided for at &sect;627.470(d) of this part, may be appealed directly to the
Secretary without prior exhaustion of local remedies. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)(1) Appeals shall be submitted to the Secretary, U.S. Department of Labor, Washington, DC 20210, ATTENTION: ASET.
A copy of the appeal shall be provided simultaneously to the Governor. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The Secretary shall not accept an appeal dated later than 30 days after receipt of written notification from the
Governor or the Secretary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The appealing party shall explain why it believes the decision to impose the reorganization plan is contrary to
the provisions of section 106 of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) The Secretary shall accept the appeal and make a decision only with regard to determining whether or not the decision
to impose the reorganization plan is inconsistent with section 106 of the Act. The Secretary may consider any comments
submitted by the Governor or the SDA, as appropriate. The Secretary shall make a final decision within 60 days after
this appeal is received (section 106(j)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00125 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.475 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Oversight and monitoring. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) The Secretary may monitor all recipients and subrecipients of financial assistance pursuant to section 163 of
the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (b) The Governor is responsible for oversight of all SDA and SSG activities and State-supported programs. The Governor
shall develop and make available for review a State monitoring plan. The plan shall specify the mechanism which: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (1) Ensures that established policies to achieve program quality and outcomes meet the objectives of the Act and regulations
promulgated thereunder; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) Enables the Governor to determine if SDA's and SSG's have demonstrated substantial compliance with the requirements
for oversight; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (3) Determines whether the Job Training Plan shall be disapproved consistent with the criteria contained in section
105(b)(1) of the Act; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (4) Regularly examines expenditures against the cost categories and cost limitations specified in the Act and these
regulations; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) Ensures that all areas of SDA and SSG operations are monitored onsite regularly, but not less than once annually;
and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (6) Provides for corrective action to be imposed if conditions in paragraphs (b)(1)&hyph;(4) of this section are
not met. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (c) The Governor shall issue instructions to SDA's and title III SSG's on the development of a substate monitoring
plan. The instructions for development of the monitoring plan, at a minimum, shall address the monitoring scope and
frequency, and the Secretary's emphasis and direction. The substate monitoring plan shall be part of the job training
plan. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (d) The Governor shall establish general standards for PIC oversight responsibilities. The required PIC standards
shall be included in the Governor's Coordination and Special Services Plan (GCSSP). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (e)(1) The PIC, pursuant to standards established by the Governor, shall establish specific policies for monitoring
and oversight of SDA performance which shall be described in the job training plan. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) The PIC shall exercise independent oversight over activities under the job training plan which shall not be circumscribed
by agreements with the appropriate chief elected official(s) of the SDA. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (f) The PIC and chief elected official(s) may conduct such oversight as they, individually or jointly, deem necessary
or delegate oversight responsibilities to an appropriate entity pursuant to their mutual agreement. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.477 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Governor's determination of substantial violation. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Except as provided at paragraph (d) of this section, if, as a result of financial and compliance audits or otherwise,
the Governor determines that there is a substantial violation of a specific provision of this Act or the regulations
under this Act, and corrective action has not been taken, the Governor shall 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (1) Issue a notice of intent to revoke approval of all or part of the plan affected; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) Impose a reorganization plan, which may include 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (i) Restructuring the private industry council involved; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (ii) Prohibiting the use of designated service providers; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (iii) Selecting an alternative entity to administer the program for the service delivery area involved; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (iv) Merging the service delivery area into 1 or more other existing service delivery areas; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (v) Other such changes as the Secretary or Governor determines necessary to secure compliance (section 164(b)(1)).

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)(1) The actions taken by the Governor pursuant to paragraph (a)(1) of this section may be appealed to the Secretary
as provided at &sect;628.426 of this chapter (section 164(b)(2)(A)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) The actions taken by the Governor pursuant to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
paragraph (a)(2) of this section may be appealed to the Secretary, as provided at &sect;627.471 of this part (section
164(b)(2)(B)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (c) Allegations that the Governor failed to promptly take the actions required under paragraph (a) of this section
shall be handled under &sect;627.607 of this part (section 164(b)(3)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (d) This section does not apply to remedial actions for SDA failures to meet performance standards, which are provided
for at &sect;627.470 of this part, and do not apply to remedial actions for the failure to comply with procurement standards,
which are provided for at &sect;627.703 of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.480 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Audits. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Non-Federal Audits.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
_(1) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Governments.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Each recipient and governmental subrecipient is responsible for complying with the Single Audit Act of 1984 (31 U.S.C.
7501&hyph;7) and 29 CFR part 96, the Department of Labor regulations which implement Office of Management and Budget
(OMB) Circular A&hyph;128, ``Audits of State and Local Governments''. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00126 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(2) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Non-governmental organizations.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Each non-governmental recipient or subrecipient shall comply with OMB Circular A&hyph;133, ``Audits of Institutions
of Higher Education and Other Nonprofit Institutions'', as implemented by the Department of Labor regulations at
29 CFR part 96. The provisions of this paragraph (a)(2) do not apply to any non-governmental organization that is:

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (i) A commercial organization; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (ii) A hospital or an institution of higher education for which State or local governments choose to apply OMB Circular
A&hyph;128. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (3) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Commercial organizations.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 A commercial organization which is a recipient or subrecipient and which receives $25,000 or more a year in Federal
financial assistance to operate a JTPA program shall have an audit that: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (i) Is usually performed annually, but not less frequently than every two years; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (ii) Is completed within one year after the end of the period covered by the audit and submitted to the awarding agency
within one month after completion; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (iii) Is either: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (A) An independent financial and compliance audit of Federal funds that includes coverage of the JTPA program within
its scope, and is conducted and prepared in accordance with generally accepted government auditing standards; or

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(B) An organization-wide audit that includes financial and compliance coverage of the JTPA program within its scope.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Federal audits.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The notice of audits conducted or arranged by the Office of Inspector General or the Comptroller General shall be provided
in advance, as required by section 165(b) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Audit reports.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1) Audit reports of recipient-level entities and other organizations which receive JTPA funds directly from the
U.S. Department of Labor shall be submitted to the Office of Inspector General. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) Audit reports of organizations other than those described in paragraph (c)(1) of this section shall be submitted
to the entity which provided the JTPA funds. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (d) Each entity that receives JTPA program funds and awards a portion of those funds to one or more subrecipients shall:

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (1) Ensure that each subrecipient complies with the applicable audit requirements; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) Resolve all audit findings that impact the JTPA program with its subrecipient and ensure that corrective action
for all such findings is instituted within 6 months after receipt of the audit report (where appropriate, corrective
action shall include debt collection action for all disallowed costs); and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00127 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(3) Maintain an audit resolution file documenting the disposition of reported questioned costs and corrective actions
taken for all findings. The ETA Grant Officer may request that an audit resolution report, as specified in paragraph
(e)(2) of this section, be submitted for such audits or may have the audit resolution reviewed through the compliance
review process. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (e)(1) Audits of recipient-level entities and other organizations which receive JTPA funds directly from DOL and
all audits conducted by or under contract for the Office of Inspector General shall be issued by the OIG to the Employment
and Training Administration after acceptance by OIG. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) After receipt of the audit report, the ETA Grant Officer shall request that the State submit an audit resolution
report documenting the disposition of the reported questioned costs, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
i.e.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
, whether allowed or disallowed, the basis for allowing questioned costs, the method of repayment planned or required,
and corrective actions, including debt collection efforts, taken or planned. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (f) If the recipient intends to propose the use of ``stand-in'' costs as substitutes for otherwise unallowable costs,
the proposal shall be included with the audit resolution report. To be considered, the proposed ``stand-in'' costs
shall have been reported as uncharged JTPA program costs, included within the scope of the audit, and accounted for
in the auditee's financial system, as required by &sect;627.425 of this part, Standards for financial management
and participant data systems. To be accepted, stand-in costs shall be from the same title, and program year as the costs
which they are proposed to replace, and shall not result in a violation of the applicable cost limitations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (g) After receiving the audit resolution report, the ETA Grant Officer shall review the report, the recipient's disposition,
and any liability waiver request submitted in accordance with &sect;627.704 of this part. If the Grant Officer agrees
with all aspects of the recipient's disposition of the audit, the Grant Officer shall so notify the recipient. If the
Grant Officer disagrees with the recipient's conclusion on specific points in the audit, the Grant Officer shall
resolve the audit through the initial and final determination process described in &sect;627.606 of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.481 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Audit resolution. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Federal audit resolution.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 When the OIG issues an audit report to the Employment and Training Administration for resolution, the ETA Grant Officer
shall provide a copy of the report to the recipient (if it does not already have the report), along with a request that
the recipient submit its audit resolution report as specified in &sect;627.480(e)(2) of this part, unless the Grant
Officer chooses to proceed directly against the recipient pursuant to &sect;627.601 of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (1) For audits of recipient-level entities and other organizations which receive JTPA funds directly from DOL, the
Grant Officer shall request that the audit resolution report be submitted within 60 days from the date that the audit
report is issued by the OIG. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) For audits of subrecipient organizations, the Grant Officer shall provide the recipient with a 180-day period
within which to resolve the audit with its subrecipient(s), and shall request that the audit resolution report be
submitted at the end of that 180-day period. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (b) After receiving the audit resolution report, the ETA Grant Officer shall review the report, the recipient's disposition,
any liability waiver request, and any proposed ``stand-in'' costs. If the Grant Officer agrees with all aspects of
the recipient's disposition of the audit, the Grant Officer shall so notify the recipient, constituting final agency
action on the audit. If the Grant Officer disagrees with the recipient's conclusion on specific points in the audit,
or if the recipient fails to submit its audit resolution report, the Grant Officer shall resolve the audit through
the initial and final determination process described in &sect;627.606 of this part. Normally, the Grant Officer's
notification of agreement (a concurrence letter) or disagreement (an initial determination) with the recipient's
audit resolution report will be provided within 180 days of the Grant Officer's receipt of the report. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Non-Federal audit resolution.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1) To ensure timely and appropriate resolution for audits of all subrecipients, including SDA grant recipients
and title III SSG's, and to ensure recipient-wide consistency, the Governor shall prescribe standards for audit
resolution and debt collection policies and procedures that shall be included in each job training plan in accordance
with section 104(b)(12) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) The Governor shall prescribe an appeals procedure for audit resolution disputes which, at a minimum, provides
for: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (i) The period of time, not less than 15 days nor more than 30 days, after the issuance of the final determination in which
an appeal may be filed; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (ii) The rules of procedure; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (iii) Timely submission of evidence; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (iv) The timing of decisions; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (v) Further appeal rights, if any. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.485 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Closeout. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
General.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The Grant Officer shall close out each annual JTPA grant agreement within a timely period after the funding period
covered by the award has expired. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00128 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(b) Revisions to the reported expenditures for a program year of funds may be made until 90 days after the time limitation
for expenditure of JTPA funds, as set forth in section 161(b) of the Act, has expired. The Grant Officer may extend this
deadline if the recipient submits a written request with justification. After that time, the Grant Officer shall
consider all reports received as final and no additional revisions may be made. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (c) When closing out a JTPA grant, the Grant Officer shall notify the recipient, by certified mail, that, since the
time limitation for expenditure of funds covered by the grant award has expired, it is the Department of Labor's intent
to close the annual grant as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (1) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Cost adjustment.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Based on receipt of reports in paragraph (b) of this section, the Grant Officer shall make upward or downward adjustments
to the allowable costs; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (2) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Cash adjustment.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 DOL shall make prompt payment to the recipient for allowable reimbursable costs; the recipient shall promptly refund
to DOL any balance of cash advanced that is in excess of allowable costs for the grant award being closed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (d) The recipient shall have an additional 60 days after the date of the notice described in paragraph (c) of this section
in which to provide the Grant Officer with information as to the reason(s) why closeout should not occur. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) At the end of the 60-day period described in paragraph (d) of this section, the Grant Officer shall notify the recipient
that closeout has occurred, unless information provided by the recipient, pursuant to paragraph (d) of this section,
indicates otherwise. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.490 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Later disallowances and adjustments after closeout. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The closeout of a grant does not affect: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (a) The Grant Officer's right to disallow costs and recover funds on the basis of a later audit or other review; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (b) The recipient's obligation to return any funds due as a result of later refunds, corrections, subrecipient audit
disallowances, or other transactions; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (c) Records retention requirements in &sect;627.460 of this part, Requirements for records, and &sect;627.463
of this part, Public access to records; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (d) Property management requirements in &sect;627.465 of this part, Property management standards; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (e) Audit and audit resolution requirements in &sect;627.480 of this part, Audits and &sect;627.481 of this part,
Audit resolution. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.495 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Collection of amounts due. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Any funds paid to a recipient in excess of the amount to which the recipient is finally determined to be entitled
under the terms of the grant constitute a debt to the Federal Government. If not paid within a reasonable period after
demand, the Secretary may take any actions permitted by law to recover the funds. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (b) The Secretary shall charge interest on an overdue debt in accordance with the Federal Claims Collection Standards
(4 CFR ch. II). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=1 -->
Subpart E_Grievances Procedures at the State and Local Level 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.500 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Scope and purpose. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
General.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 This subpart establishes the procedures which apply to the handling of noncriminal complaints under the Act at the
Governor, the SDA, and the SSG levels. Nothing contained in this subpart shall be deemed to prejudice the separate
exercise of other legal rights in pursuit of remedies and sanctions available outside the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Handling of discrimination complaints.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Complaints of discrimination pursuant to section 167(a) of the Act shall be handled under 29 CFR part 34. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Complaints and reports of criminal fraud, waste, and abuse.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Information and complaints involving criminal fraud, waste, abuse or other criminal activity shall be reported
through the Department's Incident Reporting System, directly and immediately to the DOL Office of Inspector General,
Office of Investigations, 200 Constitution Avenue NW., Room S5514, Washington, DC 20210, or to the corresponding
Regional Inspector General for Investigations, with a copy simultaneously provided to the Employment and Training
Administration. The Hotline number is 1&hyph;800&hyph;347&hyph;3756. Other complaints of a noncriminal nature
will continue to be handled under the procedures set forth in this part, subparts E and F, and through the Department's
Incident Reporting System. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (d) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Non-JTPA remedies.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Whenever any person, organization, or agency believes that a recipient, an SDA, an SSG, or other subrecipient has
engaged in conduct that violates the Act and that such conduct also violates a Federal statute other than JTPA, or a
State or local law, that person, organization, or agency may, with respect to the non-JTPA cause of action, institute
a civil action or pursue other remedies authorized under such other Federal, State, or local law against the recipient,
the SDA, the SSG, or other subrecipient, without first exhausting the remedies in this subpart. Nothing in the Act
or this chapter shall: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (1) Allow any person or organization to file a suit which alleges a violation of JTPA or regulations promulgated thereunder
without first exhausting the administrative remedies described in this subpart; or
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00129 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(2) Be construed to create a private right of action with respect to alleged violations of JTPA or the regulations promulgated
thereunder. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.501 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
State grievance and hearing procedures for noncriminal complaints at the recipient level. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a)(1) Each recipient shall maintain a recipient-level grievance procedure and shall ensure the establishment
of procedures at the SDA level and the SSG level for resolving any complaint alleging a violation of the Act, regulations
promulgated thereunder, grants, or other agreements under the Act. The procedures shall include procedures for
handling complaints and grievances arising in connection with JTPA programs operated by each SDA, SSG, and subrecipient
under the Act (section 144(a)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The procedures described in paragraph (a)(1) of this section shall also provide for resolution of complaints
arising from actions taken by the recipient with respect to investigations or monitoring reports. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The recipient's grievance hearing procedure shall require written notice to interested parties of the date,
time, and place of the hearing; an opportunity to present evidence; and a written decision. For matters under paragraph
(a)(2) of this section, the notice of hearing shall indicate the nature of the violation(s) which the hearing covers.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.502 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Grievance and hearing procedures for noncriminal complaints at the SDA and SSG levels. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Each SDA and SSG, pursuant to guidelines established by the recipient, shall establish procedures for resolving
complaints and grievances arising in connection with JTPA programs operated by the SDA, the SSG, and other subrecipients
under the Act. The procedures also shall provide for resolution of complaints arising from actions taken by the SDA
or the SSG with respect to investigations or monitoring reports of their subgrantees, contractors, and other subrecipients
(section 144(a)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) Each SDA and SSG grievance hearing procedure shall include written notice of the date, time, and place of the hearing;
an opportunity to present evidence; a written decision; and a notice of appeal rights. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) The SDA and SSG procedures shall provide for a decision within 60 days of the filing of the complaint. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.503 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Recipient-level review. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) If a complainant does not receive a decision at the SDA or the SSG level within 60 days of filing the complaint or receives
a decision unsatisfactory to the complainant, the complainant shall have the right to request a review of the complaint
by the recipient. The recipient shall issue a decision within 30 days of receipt of the complaint. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The recipient shall also provide for an independent review, by a reviewer who is independent of the JTPA program,
of a complaint initially filed at the recipient level on which a decision was not issued within 60 days of receipt of
a complaint or on which the complainant has received an adverse decision. A decision shall be made within 30 days of
receipt by the recipient. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) A request for review under the provisions of paragraphs (a) or (b) of this section shall be filed within 10 days of
receipt of the adverse decision or, if no timely decision is rendered, within 15 days from the date on which the complainant
should have received a timely decision. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) With the exception of complaints alleging violations of the labor standards under section 143 of the Act, the recipient's
decision is final unless the Secretary exercises the authority for Federal-level review in accordance with the provisions
at &sect;627.601 of this part, Complaints and grievances at the Federal level. Complaints alleging violations of
section 143 of the Act shall be handled under the procedures set forth at &sect;627.603 of this part, special handling
of labor standards violations under section 143. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.504 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Noncriminal grievance procedure at employer level. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Recipients, SDA's, SSG's, and other subrecipients shall assure that other employers, including private-for-profit
employers of participants under the Act, have a grievance procedure relating to the terms and conditions of employment
available to their participants (section 144(b)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)(1) Employers under paragraph (a) of this section may operate their own grievance system or may utilize the grievance
system established by the recipient, the SDA, or the SSG under this subpart, except as provided for in paragraph (b)(2)
of this section. Employers shall inform participants of the grievance procedures they are to follow when the participant
begins employment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) If an employer is required to use a certain grievance procedure under a covered collective bargaining agreement,
then those procedures should be followed for the handling of JTPA complaints under this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) An employer grievance system shall provide for, upon request by the complainant, a review of an employer's decision
by the SDA, or the SSG and the recipient if necessary, in accordance with &sect;&sect;627.501 and 627.502 of this part.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=56 g=1 f=1 -->
Subpart F_Federal handling of noncriminal complaints and other allegations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.600 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Scope and purpose. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00130 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) This subpart establishes the procedures which apply to the filing, handling, and reviewing of complaints at the
Federal level. Nothing in the Act or this chapter shall be construed to allow any person or organization to join or sue
the Secretary with respect to the Secretary's responsibilities under JTPA except after exhausting the remedies
in subpart E of this part and this subpart F. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) Complaints of discrimination pursuant to section 167(a) of the Act shall be handled under 29 CFR part 34. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.601 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Complaints and allegations at the Federal level. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) The types of complaints and allegations that may be received at the Federal level for review include: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Complaints for which the recipient has failed to issue a timely decision as required by &sect;627.503 of this part;

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Alleged violations of the Act and/or the regulations promulgated thereunder resulting from Federal, State,
and/or SDA and SSG monitoring and oversight reviews; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Alleged violations of the labor standards provisions at section 143 of the Act; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Alleged violations of the relocation provisions in section 141(c) of the Act; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) Other allegations of violations of the Act or the regulations promulgated thereunder. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) Upon receipt of a complaint or allegation alleging any of the violations listed in paragraph (a) of this section,
the Secretary may: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Direct the recipient to handle a complaint through local grievance procedures established under &sect;627.502
of this part; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Investigate and determine whether the recipient or subrecipient(s) are in compliance with the Act and regulations
promulgated thereunder (section 163(b) and (c)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Allegations of violations of sections 141(c) or 143 of the Act and &sect;627.503 of this part shall be handled under
paragraph (b)(2) of this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.602 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Resolution of investigative findings. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a)(1) As a result of an investigation or monitoring by the Department, or of the actions specified in paragraph (b)(2)
of &sect;627.601 of this part, the Grant Officer shall notify the recipient of the findings of the investigation and
shall give the recipient a period of time, not to exceed 60 days, depending on the nature of the findings, to comment
and to take appropriate corrective actions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The Grant Officer shall review the complete file of the investigation and the recipient's actions. The Grant Officer's
review shall take into account the sanction provisions of subpart G of this part. If the Grant Officer agrees with the
recipient's handling of the situation, the Grant Officer shall so notify the recipient. This notification shall
constitute final agency action. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) If the Grant Officer disagrees with the recipient's handling of the matter, the Grant Officer shall proceed pursuant
to &sect;627.606 of this part, Grant officer resolution. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.603 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Special handling of labor standards violations under Section 143 of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) A complaint alleging JTPA section 143 violations may be submitted to the Secretary by either party to the complaint
when: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) The complainant has exhausted the grievance procedures set forth at subpart E of this part, or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The 60-day time period specified for reaching a decision under a procedure set forth at subpart E of this part has
elapsed without a decision (section 144(a) and (d)(1)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)(1) The Secretary shall investigate the allegations contained in a complaint alleging violations of JTPA section
143, make a determination whether a violation has occurred, and issue a decision within 120 days of receipt by the Secretary
of the complaint (section 144(c) and (d)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) If the results of the Secretary's investigation indicate that a decision by a recipient under a procedure set forth
at subpart E of this part requires modification or reversal, or that the 60-day time period for decision under section
144(a) has elapsed, the Secretary shall modify, reverse, or issue such decision. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) If the Secretary modifies or reverses a decision made under a procedure set forth at subpart E of this part, or issues
a decision where the 60-day time period has elapsed without a decision, the Secretary shall offer an opportunity for
a hearing, in accordance with the procedures under section 166 of the Act and subpart H of this part (sections 144(d)(2)
and 166(a)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) If the Secretary upholds a recipient's decision, the determination is the final decision of the Secretary (section
144(d)(3)). This decision is not appealable to the Office of Administrative Law Judges. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) Except as provided in paragraph (d) of this section, remedies available under this section to a grievant for violations
of section 143 of the Act shall be limited to: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Suspension or termination of payments under the Act; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Prohibition of placement of a participant, for an appropriate period of time, in a program under the Act with an
employer that has violated section 143 of the Act, as determined under section 144(d) or (e) of the Act; and/or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Appropriate equitable relief (other than back pay) (section 144(f)(1)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00131 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(d) Available remedies for violations of section 143(a)(4), (b)(1), (b)(3), and (d) of the Act include the remedies
listed in paragraph (c) of this section, and may include the following: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Reinstatement of the grievant to the position held prior to displacement; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Payment of lost wages and benefits; and/or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Reestablishment of other relevant terms, conditions, and privileges of employment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) Nothing in this section shall be construed to prohibit a grievant from pursuing a remedy authorized under another
Federal, State, or local law for a violation of section 143 of the Act (section 144(g)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.604 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Alternative procedure for handling labor standards violations under section 143 of the Act_binding arbitration.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) A person alleging a violation of section 143 of the Act, as an alternative to processing the grievance under a procedure
described at section 144 of the Act, may submit the grievance to a binding arbitration procedure, if a collective bargaining
agreement covering the parties to the grievance so provides (section 144(e)(1)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) A person electing to have her/his complaint on JTPA section 143 labor standard violations processed under binding
arbitration provisions_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Shall choose binding arbitration before, and in lieu of, initiating a complaint under other grievance procedures
established pursuant to section 144 of the Act, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) May not elect binding arbitration for a complaint that previously has been or is subject to any other grievance
procedure established under the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) Binding arbitration decisions under the provisions of section 144(e) of the Act are not reviewable by the Secretary.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) The remedies available to a grievant under binding arbitration are limited to those set forth at section 144(f)(1)(C)
and (f)(2) of the Act (section 144(e)(2)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) Nothing in this section shall be construed to prohibit a grievant from pursuing a remedy authorized under another
Federal, State, or local law for a violation of section 143 of the Act (section 144(g)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.605 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Special Federal review of SDA- and SSG-level complaints without decision. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Should the recipient fail to provide a decision as required in &sect;627.503 of this part, the complainant may
then request from the Secretary a determination whether reasonable cause exists to believe that the Act or regulations
promulgated thereunder have been violated.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The Secretary shall act within 90 days of receipt of a request made pursuant to paragraph (a) of this section. Where
there is reasonable cause to believe the Act or regulations promulgated thereunder have been violated, the Secretary
shall direct the recipient to issue a decision adjudicating the dispute pursuant to recipient and local procedures.
The Secretary's action does not constitute final agency action and is not appealable under the Act (sections 166(a)
and 144(c)). If the recipient does not comply with the Secretary's order within 60 days, the Secretary may impose a
sanction upon the recipient for failing to issue a decision. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) A request pursuant to paragraph (a) of this section shall be filed no later than 15 days from the date on which the
complainant should have received a decision as required in &sect;627.503 of this part. The complaint shall contain
the following: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) The full name, telephone number (if any), and address (if any) of the person making the complaint; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The full name and address of the respondent against whom the complaint is made; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) A clear and concise statement of the facts, including pertinent dates, constituting the alleged violation; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00132 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(4) The provisions of the Act, regulations promulgated thereunder, grant, or other agreement under the Act believed
to have been violated; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) A statement disclosing whether proceedings involving the subject of the request have been commenced or concluded
before any Federal, State, or local authority, and, if so, the date of such commencement or conclusion, the name and
address of the authority, and the style of the case; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(6) A statement of the date the complaint was filed with the recipient, the date on which the recipient should have issued
decision, and an attestation that no decision was issued. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d)(1) A request pursuant to paragraph (a) of this section will be considered to have been filed when the Secretary
receives from the complainant a written statement sufficiently precise to evaluate the complaint and the grievance
procedure used by the recipient, the SDA, or the SSG. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) When an imprecise request is received within the 15-day period prescribed in paragraph (a) of this section, the
Secretary may extend the period for submission. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.606 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Grant Officer resolution. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) When the Grant Officer is dissatisfied with the State's disposition of an audit, as specified in &sect;627.481
of this part, or other resolution of violations (including those arising out of incident reports or compliance reviews),
with the recipient's response to findings resulting from investigations pursuant to &sect;627.503 of this part,
or if the recipient fails to comply with the Secretary's decision pursuant to &sect;627.605(b) of this part, the initial
and final determination process shall be used to resolve the matter. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Initial determination.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The Grant Officer shall make an initial determination on the findings for both those matters where there is agreement
and those where there is disagreement with the recipient's resolution, including the allowability of questioned
costs or activities. Such initial determination shall be based upon the requirements of the Act, regulations promulgated
thereunder, grants, contracts, or other agreements under the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Informal resolution.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The Grant Officer shall not revoke a recipient's grant in whole or in part, nor institute corrective actions or sanctions,
without first providing the recipient with an opportunity to present documentation or arguments to resolve informally
those matters in controversy contained in the initial determination. The initial determination shall provide for
an informal resolution period which shall be at least 60 days from issuance of the initial determination. If the matters
are resolved informally, the Grant Officer shall issue a final determination pursuant to paragraph (d) of this section
which notifies the parties in writing of the nature of the resolution and may close the file. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Grant Officer's final determination.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1) If the matter is not fully resolved informally, the Grant Officer shall provide each party with a written final
determination by certified mail, return receipt requested. For audits of recipient-level entities and other recipients
which receive JTPA funds directly from DOL, ordinarily the final determination will be issued not later than 180 days
from the date that the OIG issues the final approved audit report to the Employment and Training Administration. For
audits of subrecipients conducted by the OIG, ordinarily the final determination will be issued not later than 360
days from the date the OIG issues the final approved audit report to ETA. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) A final determination under this paragraph (d) shall: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Indicate that efforts to informally resolve matters contained in the initial determination have been unsuccessful;

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) List those matters upon which the parties continue to disagree; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) List any modifications to the factual findings and conclusions set forth in the initial determination; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iv) Establish a debt, if appropriate; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00133 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(v) Require corrective action when needed; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(vi) Determine liability, method of restitution of funds and sanctions; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(vii) Offer an opportunity for a hearing in accordance with subpart H of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Unless a hearing is requested, a final determination under this paragraph (d) constitutes final agency action
and is not subject to further review. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) Nothing in this section shall preclude the Grant Officer from issuing an initial determination and/or final determination
directly to a subrecipient, in accordance with section 164(e)(3) of the Act. In such a case, the Grant Officer shall
inform the recipient of such action. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
627.607 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Grant Officer resolution of Governor's failure to promptly take action. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) An allegation, whether arising from a complaint, from monitoring or other information available to the Department,
that a Governor failed to promptly take remedial action of a substantial violation of the Act or the regulations under
this Act, as required by &sect;627.477 of this part, shall be promptly investigated by the Department. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The Grant Officer shall notify the Governor of the findings of the investigation or monitoring and shall give the
Governor a period of time, not to exceed 30 days, to comment on the nature of the findings and to take appropriate corrective
actions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) The Grant Officer shall review the complete file of the investigation, monitoring, and the Governor's actions.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) If the Grant Officer determines that, (1) as a result financial and compliance audits or otherwise, the Governor
determined that there was a substantial violation of a specific provision of the Act or the regulations under this
Act, and corrective action had not been taken and, (2) the Grant Officer determines that the Governor has not taken
the actions required by &sect;627.477(a), the Grant Officer shall take such actions required by &sect;627.477(a).

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) The Grant Officer's determination, unless a hearing is requested, constitutes final agency action and is not
subject to further review. (Section 164(b)(3)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=1 -->
Subpart G_Sanctions for Violations of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.700 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Purpose and scope. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This subpart describes the sanctions and appropriate corrective actions that may be imposed by the Secretary for
violations of the Act, regulations promulgated thereunder, or grant terms and conditions (sections 106(j)(5),
164 (b), (d), (e), (f), (g), and (h)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.702 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Sanctions and corrective actions.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Except for actions under sections 106(j), 164 (b) and (f), and 167 of the Act and the funding restrictions specified
at &sect;627.423 of this part, Funding restrictions for ``high-risk'' recipients and subrecipients, the Grant
Officer shall utilize initial and final determination procedures outlined in &sect;627.606, Grant Officer resolution,
of this part to impose a sanction or corrective action. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) To impose a sanction or corrective action regarding a violation of section 167 of the Act, the Department shall
utilize the procedures of 29 CFR part 34. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) To impose a sanction or corrective action for failure to meet performance standards, where the recipient has not
acted as required at section 106(j)(4), the Grant Officer shall utilize the procedures set forth at &sect;627.470
(d) and (f). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) To impose a sanction or corrective action for noncompliance with the procurement standards provisions set forth
at &sect;&sect;627.420 and 627.703 of this part, where the recipient has not acted, the Grant Officer may utilize
the procedures set forth at section 164(b) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) To impose a sanction or corrective action for the Governor's failure to promptly take remedial action of a substantial
violation as required by &sect;627.477 of this part, the Grant Officer shall utilize the procedure set forth in &sect;627.607
of this part.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(f) The recipient shall be held responsible for all funds under its grant(s). The recipient shall hold subrecipients,
including SDA's and SSG's, responsible for JTPA funds received through the grant, and may ultimately hold the units
of local government which constitute the SDA or the SSG responsible for such funds. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(g) Nothing in this section shall preclude the Grant Officer from imposing a sanction directly against a subrecipient,
as authorized in section 164(e)(3) of the Act. In such a case, the Grant Officer shall inform the recipient of such action.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.703 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Failure to comply with procurement provisions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) If, as part of the recipient's annual on-site monitoring of its SDA's/SSG's, the recipient determines that an
SDA/SSG is not in compliance with the procurement requirements established in accordance with the provisions at
section 164(a)(3) of the Act and &sect;627.420, of this part, Procurement, and &sect;627.422 of this part, Selection
of service providers, the recipient shall: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Require corrective action to secure prompt compliance; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Impose the sanctions provided for under the provisions at section 164(b) if the recipient finds that the SDA/SSG
has failed to take timely corrective action under paragraph (a)(1) of this section (section 164(a) (4) and (5)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) An action by the recipient to impose a sanction against either an SDA or SSG, in accordance with this section, may
be appealed to the Secretary under the same terms and conditions as the disapproval of the respective plan, or plan
modification, as set forth at &sect;628.426(e), Review and approval (section 164(b)(2)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) If, upon a determination under paragraph (a)(2) of this section to impose a sanction under section 164(b) of the
Act, the recipient fails to promptly take the actions required under paragraph (a)(2) of this section, the Secretary
shall take such actions against the recipient or the SDA/SSG as appropriate (section 164(b)(3)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.704 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Process for waiver of State liability. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) A recipient may request a waiver of liability as described in section 164(e)(2) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)(1) When the debt for which a waiver of liability is desired was established in a non-Federal resolution, such requests
shall be accompanied by a resolution report. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) When the ETA Grant Officer is resolving the finding(s) for which a waiver of liability is desired, such request
shall be made no later than the informal resolution period described in &sect;627.606(c) of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00134 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(c) A waiver of the recipient's liability can only be considered by the Grant Officer when the misexpenditure of JTPA
funds: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Occurred at a subrecipient level; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Was not a violation of section 164(e)(1) of the Act, or did not constitute fraud; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) If fraud did exist, it was perpetrated against the recipient/subrecipient; and: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) The recipient/subrecipient discovered, investigated, reported, and prosecuted the perpetrator of said fraud;
and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) After aggressive debt collection action, it can be documented that there is no likelihood of collection from
the perpetrator of the fraud. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) The recipient has issued a final determination which disallows the misexpenditure, the recipient's appeal process
has been exhausted, and a debt has been established; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) The recipient requests such a waiver and provides documentation to demonstrate that it has substantially complied
with the requirements of section 164(e)(2)(A), (B), (C), and (D) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) The recipient shall not be released from liability for misspent funds under the determination required by section
164(e) of the Act unless the Grant Officer determines that further collection action, either by the recipient or subrecipient,
would be inappropriate or would prove futile. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.706 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Process for advance approval of a recipient's contemplated corrective actions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) The recipient may request advance approval from the Grant Officer for contemplated corrective actions, including
debt collection actions, which the recipient plans to initiate or to forego. The recipient's request shall include
a description and an assessment of all actions taken by the subrecipient to collect the misspent funds. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) Based on the recipient's request, the Grant Officer may determine that the recipient may forego certain collection
actions against a subrecipient where: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) The subrecipient was not at fault with respect to the liability criteria set forth in section 164(e)(2)(A), (B),
(C), and (D) of the Act; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The misexpenditure of funds: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Was not made by that subrecipient but by an entity that received JTPA funds from that subrecipient; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Was not a violation of section 164(e)(1) of the Act, or did not constitute fraud; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) If fraud did exist, it was perpetrated against the subrecipient, and: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(A) The subrecipient discovered, investigated, reported, and prosecuted the perpetrator of said fraud; and
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(B) After aggressive debt collection action, it can be documented that there is no likelihood of collection from the
perpetrator of the fraud. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) A final determination which disallows the misexpenditure and establishes a debt has been issued at the appropriate
level; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Final action within the recipient's appeal system has been completed; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) Further debt collection action by that subrecipient or the recipient would be either inappropriate or futile.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.708 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Offset process. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) In accordance with section 164(d) of the Act, the primary sanction for misexpenditure of JTPA funds is repayment.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) A recipient may request that a debt, or a portion thereof, be offset against amounts allotted to the recipient,
and retained at the recipient level for administrative costs, under the current or a future JTPA entitlement. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) For title II grants, any offset shall be applied against the recipient level 5 percent administrative cost set-aside
only and may not be distributed by the recipient among its subrecipients. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) For title III grants, any such offset must be applied against that portion of funds reserved by the recipient for
recipient level administration only and may not be distributed by the recipient among its subrecipients. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) The Grant Officer may approve an offset request, under section 164(d) of the Act, if the misexpenditures were not
in violation of section 164(e)(1) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) If offset is granted, the debt shall not be fully satisfied until the Grant Officer reduces amounts allotted to
the State by the amount of the misexpenditure. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) The recipient shall not have the authority to reduce allocations to an SDA or SSG for misexpenditure of JTPA funds
under section 164(d) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=1 -->
Subpart H_Hearings by the Office of Administrative Law Judges
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.800 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Scope and Purpose. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) The jurisdiction of the Office of the Administrative Law Judges (OALJ) extends only to those complainants identified
in sections 141(c), 144(d), 164(f), and 166(a) of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) Actions arising under section 167 of the Act shall be handled under 29 CFR part 34. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) All other disputes arising under the Act shall be adjudicated under the appropriate recipient or subrecipient
grievance procedures or other applicable law. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.801 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Procedures for filing request for hearing. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Within 21 days of receipt of a final determination imposing a sanction or corrective action or denying financial
assistance, the applicant, the recipient, the SDA, the SSG, or other subrecipient, or a vendor against which the Grant
Officer has imposed a sanction or corrective action may appeal the Grant Officer's determination to the OALJ. A request
for a hearing shall be transmitted by certified mail, return receipt requested, to the Chief Administrative Law Judge,
U.S. Department of Labor, 800 K Street, NW., Suite 400, Washington, DC 20001, with one copy to the departmental official
who issued the determination. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The 21-day filing requirement in paragraph (a) of this section is jurisdictional. Failure to timely request a
hearing acts as a waiver of the right to hearing. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) A request for a hearing under this section shall state specifically those issues of the final determination upon
which review is requested. Those provisions of the final determination not specified for review, or the entire final
determination when no hearing has been requested within the 21 days, shall be considered resolved and not subject
to further review. Only alleged violations of the Act, regulations promulgated thereunder, grant or other agreement
under the Act fairly raised in the determination and the request for hearing are subject to review. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940902-0-00135 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940902-0-00010 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(d) The procedures set forth in this subpart apply in the case of a complainant who has not had a dispute adjudicated
under the alternative dispute resolution process set forth in &sect;627.805 of this part within 60 days, except that
the request for hearing before the OALJ must be filed within 15 days of the conclusion of the 60-day period. In addition
to including the final determination upon which review is requested, the complainant shall include a copy of any Stipulation
of Facts and a brief summary of proceedings.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.802 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Rules of procedure.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) The rules of practice and procedure promulgated by the OALJ, at subpart A of 29 CFR part 18, shall govern the conduct
of hearings under this section, except that a request for hearing under this section shall not be considered a complaint
to which the filing of an answer by DOL or a DOL agency or official is required. Technical rules of evidence shall not
apply to hearings conducted pursuant to this part; however, rules or principles designed to assure production of
the most credible evidence available and to subject testimony to cross-examination shall apply.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Prehearing procedures.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 In all cases, the ALJ should encourage the use of prehearing procedures to simplify and to clarify facts and issues.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Subpoenas.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Subpoenas necessary to secure the attendance of witnesses and the production of documents or things at hearings shall
be obtained from the ALJ and shall be issued pursuant to the authority contained in section 163(b) of the Act, incorporating
15 U.S.C. 49.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Timely submission of evidence.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The ALJ shall not permit the introduction at the hearing of any documentation if such documentation has not been made
available for review by the other parties to the proceeding either at the time ordered for any prehearing conference,
or, in the absence of such an order, at least 3 weeks prior to the hearing date.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Burden of production.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The Grant Officer shall have the burden of production to support her or his decision. To this end, the Grant Officer
shall prepare and file an administrative file in support of the decision which shall be made part of the record. Thereafter,
the party or parties seeking to overturn the Grant Officer's decision shall have the burden of persuasion.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.803 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Relief.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
In ordering relief, the ALJ shall have the full authority of the Secretary under section 164 of the Act.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.804 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Timing of decisions.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The ALJ should render a written decision not later than 90 days after the closing of the record.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.805 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Alternative dispute resolution.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Parties to a complaint under &sect;627.801 of this part, Procedures for filing a request for hearing, may choose
to waive their rights to an administrative hearing before the OALJ by choosing to transfer the settlement of their
dispute to an individual acceptable to all parties for the purpose of conducting an informal review of the stipulated
facts and rendering a decision in accordance with applicable law. A written decision will be issued within 60 days
after the matter is submitted for informal review.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The waiver of the right to request a hearing before the OALJ may be revoked if a settlement has not been reached or
a decision has not been issued within the 60 days provided in paragraph (a) of this section.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) The decision rendered under this informal review process shall be treated as a final decision of an Administrative
Law Judge pursuant to section 166(b) of the Act.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.806 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Other authority.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Nothing contained in this subpart shall be deemed to prejudice the separate exercise of other legal rights in pursuit
of remedies and sanctions available outside the Act.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=1 -->
Subpart I_Transition Provisions
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;627.900 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Scope and purpose.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
